	   <a name=99440675891387></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f99440675891387><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=11&mid=99440675891387>Wizard Tactics</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=11&mid=99440675891387#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Jul 6th 4:05 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>This will be my fist post so bare with me if I ramble.<br><br>&nbsp;&nbsp; Wizards are really pathetic until you get Bonds of Force.  It will, if you are like me, turn instantly into one of your most cast spells.  I started quading as soon as I got it.  You may not have sow but you have teleports.  Go hang out at a druid ring and get one then gate back to your hunting ground.  I also carry sow potions in case it wears off.  I hunt only in large open places with many non-casting mobs that run the same speeds.   I either cast early level fast casting nukes or run right through the monster to pull (defense is free AC).  I run like mobs over each other until I have 4.   I run around them in a circle until they are very close together then run away until they are out of range for bonds of force and try to cast it until they are in range.  If you hit all four it is an easy matter to run away and AE nuke them till they drop.  I suggest refreshing the spell mid pull until you get no resists if it is questionable if you will kill them before it wears off.  If it hits it lasts a set time get a feel for when it will wear off.  If you get a resist or adds group them all up just like you would four of them and bonds of force the grouping.  Target what runs free from it and snare them as well.  Pull them back together if you only have four or pick a grouping.  Nuke them till they drop.  If you have pulled too many let the bonds of force spell wear off and regather them.  I have done up to eight mobs in this fashion.  Do not pull like druids do by snaring each one if you can help it unless they run faster than the cast time of bonds of force adn its range. (i.e. snow cougars)  You waste mana and time that could be spent medding fussing and getting them together.  The doesn't last as long as a druid but we drop them much faster.  I solo from 34 to 43 in four days of dedicated kiting.  I also port on the side for money and clarity.  I like to kite things 5 levels below me because of the ease and rate.  As they get tougher they get a lot more hit points and it is better to do two easy pulls than one hard pull.  You will get more xp and loot if you pick the right targets.  I offer some suggestions for safty too.  Gate has a low casting time and is mana cheap.  Bind in the opposite direction from where you kite.  If a pull looks bad or you have too many targets, gate and come back.  Yonder is worth knowing how to use.  Get used to the sudden shift and it will give you time to cast gate vs most things.  Don't just cast yonder and start casting gate.  Cast until you know they are far enough away and then go.  I have saved my life many many times because I know how to use it.  (also nice in outdoor groups because if you out range the monster you lose a lot of aggro and while you are walking back the group will take its attention from you)  Don't give up hope on the Wizard they are a mighty class but take skill to play.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
